    	<annotation>	
    		
            	<!-- Marginalia -->
    		
        		<marginalia hand="Italian">
        			<language ident="LA">
            			<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    				<marginalia_text>
                    					S'oli sunt pra[e]gnantissimi Loci Communes: et 
                      				</marginalia_text>
            			</position>
        				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
        					<marginalia_text>
        						pauca[e] pra[e]potentes materia[e],
        						qua[e] a[e]dificant egregiu[m] pragmaticu[m].
        					</marginalia_text>
        					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
        				</position>
        			</language>
        			<translation>
        				Only common places are most pregnant, those few superior matters 
        				which contribute to an exceptional pragmatics. 
        			</translation>
        		</marginalia>
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Ne quis fallatur  pomposis )
    						) professoru[m] pollicitationibus:
    						qua[e] tandem &egrave; libris ingens spes,
    						cum sapientissimi Papa[e], post 
    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						omnia auctoru[m] monumenta peruolutata, nihil
    						iudicarint maius, aut sua meditatione dignius,
    						quam Homerum, Horatium, Martialem?
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Homer"/>
    					<person name="Horace"/>
    					<person name="Martial"/>
    					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				 Who indeed is deceived by the pompous promises of the professors? 
    				 Promises which, after all, are an immoderate expectation from books, 
    				 since the wisest popes, after thoroughly considering all the great works,  
    				 judged that nothing be greater, or more worthy of their meditation, 
    				 than Homer, Horace, and Martial?  				 
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
    		
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Strategema. 
    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				Stratagem.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						G.R. non credebat Deo; sed credebat Proditori. 
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Girolamo Ruscelli"/>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				Girolamo Ruscelli did not believe in God, but he believed in betrayal. 
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
        
        
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position place="left_margin" book_orientation="270">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Erg&ograve; statim perlustranda omnia monumenta: penetrandi potiss[im]u[m]
    						Loci Communes: et sola curanda personaru[m], reru[m], actionu[m] potentiss[im]a.
    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				Therefore, all books must immediately be examined: above all, penetrating common places. And only those
    				most potent matters concerning people, things, and actions must be taken into consideration.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
        
